post_text:
Frontier High School will be having a graduation celebration at 1:00 PM on May 16th in the Superintendent parking lot. Each car will have to have a ticket to enter the parking lot. Graduates will receive 4 tickets each to distribute to family and friends. Students, family, and guests will arrive and watch the celebration from their cars. Social distancing regulations must be followed. If you do not have a ticket and would like to watch the graduation celebration it will be live-streamed on our school facebook page.

Frontier will also be sending out a recorded video of a virtual graduation ceremony with Valedictorian and Salutatorian speeches as well as the Senior slideshow. This video will posted May 16th on the school's webpage ( http://www.frontierok.com/ ) and on Frontier's Facebook page ( Frontier Public Schools ISD I004 ).

post_text:
It is with great sadness, that we inform our Patrons that on April 9th, Phyllis Carpenter passed away. Phyllis was a long time Elementary teacher at Frontier Schools and Marland. She was beloved by her students and co-workers. She influenced an entire generation of Frontier students in a positive way. Every single student in her class felt LOVED. If you wish to share your stories or condolances to her family go to this link
https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/swtimes/obituary.aspx?pid=195935375

See the below guidelines if you are getting the meals Frontier is providing.

Food Safety, Storage and Reheat Instructions

To save as a leftover food, the student must put the food in cold storage by 2:30

Unless saved as a leftover, the student should consume the food by 4:30 or discard.

STORAGE INSTRUCTIONS:
Cool Food Rapidly
To prevent bacterial growth, it’s important to cool food rapidly by the time above so it reaches as fast as possible the safe refrigerator-storage temperature of 40° F or below.
Store Leftovers Safely
Leftovers can be kept in the refrigerator for 4 or 5 days or frozen (0° F or below) for 3 to 4 months.

REHEAT INSTRUCTIONS:
Entrees: Beef Taco, Breaded Chicken…

Chisholm Broadband who owns Encounter wireless is offering a reduced rate of $39.99 per household for internet access for the months of April through June.
Frontier Schools will pay for all households that are financially unable to afford the reduced rate and meet these criteria.
Live in our district
Have Frontier Students in your household

If applicable to you, please email your child’s Principal with the following information:
Parent/Guardian Name
Students name/names
Physical address (must be in our district)
Cell #
How many, if any, computers/chromebooks that you have in your home available for your student to use.

Email information to:
PK-6 jera.kiespert@frontierok.com
7-12 bud.valerius@frontierok.com

Someone will be contacting you from Encounter for installation instructions.
If you currently have internet through Encounter, contact them about the reduced rate.

Www.frontierok.com

Today the State Board of Education voted to suspend all in-person instruction and extracurricular activities for the remainder of the school year.
Beginning April 6, Frontier will implement continuous learning plans that will allow students to complete the school year at home.
State education and health officials believe this move will help our state fight the spread of COVID-19.
We are saddened that for many of our students, especially our Seniors, this is disappointing news. Will you graduate on time- YES, Will you have a ceremony at school- WE HOPE SO- (maybe delayed, we can’t predict the future, but we will figure something out.)

We understand that you have many questions-…

Frontier Drive By Parade TOMORROW!!
We miss our students and want to give them a shout out. We will have a parade of cars going through the community to honk and wave - we will get through this together!
Please stand in your yard away from the street and wave as we come by. Be safe and DO NOT gather in groups or approach the vehicles. We look forward to seeing all your faces!
Tentative Parade Route:
1st RED ROCK 1:10 to 1:30 (we will drive the outer streets starting with Mckinnley)
2nd Marland 1:45 to 2pm ( hwy and then around main section)
3rd Village 2:15 to 2:30 (enter north side and snake through)
Blue meadows 2:30 to 2:40

shared_text:
Kay County Health Department OK
March 24 at 7:56 AM ·

Kay County Health Department Providing Limited COVID-19 Testing

The Kay County Health Department in cooperation with the City of Ponca City, Kay County Emergency Management, and other community partners will provide a COVID-19 drive-through testing clinic. Supplies are limited and testing will focus on individuals in Kay County at highest risk.

When: March 25, 2020 from 10:00 am – 2:00 pm (as supplies last)
Where: Ponca City RecPlex, 1604 W. Grand Ave., Ponca City, OK
Enter at the West Grand Ave. Entrance

In order to be tested you must:
1. Be 18 years of age or older
2. Have fever greater than 100.4°F AND a cough or shortness of breath
* Only one person per household will be tested

Do not come for testing if:
1. You have already been practicing social distancing in the last two weeks (remain at home, telework, etc.)
2. You know you have been in contact with a person who has been diagnosed with COVID-19 within the last 14 days

REMINDER- SCHOOL IS CLOSED UNTIL APRIL 6
Starting Monday, March 23, we will be providing meals for our students at various drop off sites.
Details of the drop off locations and times will be posted as they become available.
As dictated by the Oklahoma State Department of Education, there will be no mandatory instruction online or otherwise during the school closure. Our teachers may communicate through their classroom reminder app or through school email to provide our students with a multitude of online educational tools. Parents may choose to encourage their students to continue moving forward with their education.
No mandatory assignments may be given, and no grades will be taken.

REMINDER- SCHOOL IS CLOSED UNTIL APRIL 6
Starting Monday, March 23, we will be providing meals for our students at various drop off sites.
Details of the drop off locations and times will be posted as they become available.
As dictated by the Oklahoma State Department of Education, there will be no mandatory instruction online or otherwise during the school closure. Our teachers may communicate through their classroom reminder app or through school email to provide our students with a multitude of online educational tools. Parents may choose to encourage their students to continue moving forward with their education.
No mandatory assignments may be given, and no grades will be taken.

post_text:
Practical tips for Parents during Flu season, as well as advice for those worried about Corona Virus.

If your child is running a fever keep them home, if they begin to experience additional symptoms such as vomiting, diarrhea, persistent coughing, then take them to see a Doctor.
Follow Doctors advice and inform the school of the diagnosis. Do not send children to school until they have gone 24 hours without a fever. (This is as much for your child’s protection as for others)

Please see additional resources on our web page
